You can use the `@ManyToMany` annotation to establish the many-to-many relationship between the `Tree` and `Node` entities without using a bridge entity:

Tree:

    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;tree&quot;)
    @AllArgsConstructor
    @NoArgsConstructor
    @Getter
    @Setter
    @JsonNaming(PropertyNamingStrategies.SnakeCaseStrategy.class)
    public class Tree {
        @EmbeddedId
        private TreeIdentifier treeIdentifier;
        private LocalDateTime creationDate;
    
        @ManyToMany
        @JoinTable(
                name = &quot;tree_node&quot;,
                joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = &quot;tree_id&quot;),
                inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = &quot;node_id&quot;)
        )
        private List&lt;Node&gt; nodes;
    }

Node:

    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;node&quot;)
    @AllArgsConstructor
    @NoArgsConstructor
    @Getter
    @Setter
    @JsonNaming(PropertyNamingStrategies.SnakeCaseStrategy.class) 
    public class Node {
        @EmbeddedId
        private NodeIdentifier nodeIdentifier;
        private Long nodePosition;
    
        @ManyToMany(mappedBy = &quot;nodes&quot;)
        private List&lt;Tree&gt; trees;
    }

In the `Tree` class, a `@ManyToMany` annotation to define the many-to-many relationship with the `Node` class. Specified the `@JoinTable` annotation to define the join table name and the join columns that link the `Tree` entity to the join table. The `inverseJoinColumns` attribute specifies the join columns that link the `Node` entity to the join table.

In the `Node` class, a `@ManyToMany` annotation with the `mappedBy` attribute, which tells `JPA` that the `nodes` field is the inverse side of the relationship and that the owning side is the `Tree` entity. This avoids creating a separate join entity to represent the many-to-many association.

Update:

    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;tree_node&quot;)
    @AllArgsConstructor
    @NoArgsConstructor
    @Getter
    @Setter
    @JsonNaming(PropertyNamingStrategies.SnakeCaseStrategy.class)
    public class TreeNode {
        @EmbeddedId
        private TreeNodeId treeNodeId;
        
        @MapsId(&quot;treeId&quot;)
        @ManyToOne
        private Tree tree;
        
        @MapsId(&quot;nodeId&quot;)
        @ManyToOne
        private Node node;
    }
    
    @Embeddable
    @AllArgsConstructor
    @NoArgsConstructor
    @Getter
    @Setter
    @JsonNaming(PropertyNamingStrategies.SnakeCaseStrategy.class)
    public class TreeNodeId implements Serializable {
        private String treeId;
        private String nodeId;
        
        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            return Objects.hash(treeId, nodeId);
        }
        
        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object obj) {
            if (this == obj)
                return true;
            if (obj == null || getClass() != obj.getClass())
                return false;
            TreeNodeId that = (TreeNodeId) obj;
            return Objects.equals(treeId, that.treeId) &amp;&amp; Objects.equals(nodeId, that.nodeId);
        }
    }

`TreeNode` has a composite primary key `TreeNodeId` that consists of the primary keys of both `Tree` and `Node` entities. The `tree` and `node` associations are mapped using `@MapsId`, which tells `JPA` to use the same primary key as the `TreeNodeId`

